1. Introduction -> 1.1 Changes to RFC 15:
{
    "1. Introduction -> 1.1 Changes to RFC 1541": [
        {
            "Original": "This document updates the DHCP protocol specification that appears inRFC1541.",
            "Adjusted": "This document updates the DHCP protocol specification that appears in RFC 1541."
        },
        {
            "Original": "A new DHCP message type, DHCPINFORM, has been added; see section 3.4, 4.3 and 4.4 for details.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The classing mechanism for identifying DHCP clients to DHCP servers has been extended to include \"vendor\" classes as defined in sections 4.2 and 4.3.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The minimum lease time restriction has been removed.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Finally, many editorial changes have been made to clarify the text as a result of experience gained in DHCP interoperability tests.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

3. The Client-Server Protocol -> 3.4 Obt:
{
    "3. The Client-Server Protocol -> 3.4 Obtaining parameters with externally configured network address": [
        {
            "Original": "If a client has obtained a network address through some other means (e.g., manual configuration), it may use a DHCPINFORM request message to obtain other local configuration parameters.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Servers receiving a DHCPINFORM message construct a DHCPACK message with any local configuration parameters appropriate for the client without: allocating a new address, checking for an existing binding, filling in 'yiaddr' or including lease time parameters.",
            "Adjusted": "Servers receiving a DHCPINFORM message construct a DHCPACK message with any local configuration parameters appropriate for the client without allocating a new address, checking for an existing binding, filling in 'yiaddr' or including lease time parameters."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The servers SHOULD unicast the DHCPACK reply to the address given in the 'ciaddr' field of the DHCPINFORM message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server SHOULD check the network address in a DHCPINFORM message for consistency, but MUST NOT check for an existing lease.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server forms a DHCPACK message containing the configuration parameters for the requesting client and sends the DHCPACK message directly to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

1. Introduction -> 1.3 Problem definitio:
{
    "1. Introduction -> 1.3 Problem definition and issues": [
        {
            "Original": "DHCP is designed to supply DHCP clients with the configuration parameters defined in the Host Requirements RFCs.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "After obtaining parameters via DHCP, a DHCP client should be able to exchange packets with any other host in the Internet.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The TCP/IP stack parameters supplied by DHCP are listed inAppendix A.",
            "Adjusted": "The TCP/IP stack parameters supplied by DHCP are listed in Appendix A."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Not all of these parameters are required for a newly initialized client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client and server may negotiate for the transmission of only those parameters required by the client or specific to a particular subnet.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "DHCP allows but does not require the configuration of client parameters not directly related to the IP protocol.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "DHCP also does not address registration of newly configured clients with the Domain Name System (DNS) [12, 13].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "DHCP is not intended for use in configuring routers.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

1. Introduction -> 1.5 Terminology:
{
    "1.5 Terminology": [
        {
            "Original": "This document uses the following terms: o \"DHCP client\" A DHCP client is an Internet host using DHCP to obtain configuration parameters such as a network address.",
            "Adjusted": "This document uses the following terms: \"DHCP client\" - A DHCP client is an Internet host using DHCP to obtain configuration parameters such as a network address."
        },
        {
            "Original": "o \"DHCP server\" A DHCP server is an Internet host that returns configuration parameters to DHCP clients.",
            "Adjusted": "\"DHCP server\" - A DHCP server is an Internet host that returns configuration parameters to DHCP clients."
        },
        {
            "Original": "o \"BOOTP relay agent\" A BOOTP relay agent or relay agent is an Internet host or router that passes DHCP messages between DHCP clients and DHCP servers.",
            "Adjusted": "\"BOOTP relay agent\" - A BOOTP relay agent or relay agent is an Internet host or router that passes DHCP messages between DHCP clients and DHCP servers."
        },
        {
            "Original": "DHCP is designed to use the same relay agent behavior as specified in the BOOTP protocol specification.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "o \"binding\" A binding is a collection of configuration parameters, including at least an IP address, associated with or \"bound to\" a DHCP client.",
            "Adjusted": "\"binding\" - A binding is a collection of configuration parameters, including at least an IP address, associated with or \"bound to\" a DHCP client."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Bindings are managed by DHCP servers.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

3. The Client-Server Protocol -> 3.6 Use:
{
    "3.6 Use of DHCP in clients with multiple interfaces": [
        {
            "Original": "A client with multiple network interfaces must use DHCP through each interface independently to obtain configuration information parameters for those separate interfaces.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

3. The Client-Server Protocol -> 3.3 Int:
{
    "3. The Client-Server Protocol -> 3.3 Interpretation and representation of time values": [
        {
            "Original": "A client acquires a lease for a network address for a fixed period of time (which may be infinite).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Throughout the protocol, times are to be represented in units of seconds.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The time value of 0xffffffff is reserved to represent \"infinity\".",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "As clients and servers may not have synchronized clocks, times are represented in DHCP messages as relative times, to be interpreted with respect to the client's local clock.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Representing relative times in units of seconds in an unsigned 32 bit word gives a range of relative times from 0 to approximately 100 years, which is sufficient for the relative times to be measured using DHCP.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The algorithm for lease duration interpretation given in the previous paragraph assumes that client and server clocks are stable relative to each other.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If there is drift between the two clocks, the server may consider the lease expired before the client does.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "To compensate, the server may return a shorter lease duration to the client than the server commits to its local database of client information.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

2. Protocol Summary -> 2.1 Configuration:
{
    "2.1 Configuration parameters repository": [
        {
            "Original": "The first service provided by DHCP is to provide persistent storage of network parameters for network clients.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The model of DHCP persistent storage is that the DHCP service stores a key-value entry for each client, where the key is some unique identifier (for example, an IP subnet number and a unique identifier within the subnet) and the value contains the configuration parameters for the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For example, the key might be the pair (IP-subnet-number, hardware- address) (note that the \"hardware-address\" should be typed by the type of hardware to accommodate possible duplication of hardware addresses resulting from bit-ordering problems in a mixed-media, bridged network) allowing for serial or concurrent reuse of a hardware address on different subnets, and for hardware addresses that may not be globally unique.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Alternately, the key might be the pair (IP-subnet-number, hostname), allowing the server to assign parameters intelligently to a DHCP client that has been moved to a different subnet or has changed hardware addresses (perhaps because the network interface failed and was replaced).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The protocol defines that the key will be (IP-subnet-number, hardware-address) unless the client explicitly supplies an identifier using the 'client identifier' option.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client can query the DHCP service to retrieve its configuration parameters.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client interface to the configuration parameters repository consists of protocol messages to request configuration parameters and responses from the server carrying the configuration parameters.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

4. Specification of the DHCP client-serv:
{
    "4. Specification of the DHCP client-server protocol": [
        {
            "Original": "In this section, we assume that a DHCP server has a block of network addresses from which it can satisfy requests for new addresses.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Each server also maintains a database of allocated addresses and leases in local permanent storage.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

1. Introduction -> 1.4 Requirements:
{
    "1.4 Requirements": [
        {
            "Original": "Throughout this document, the words that are used to define the significance of particular requirements are capitalized.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "These words are: o \"MUST\" This word or the adjective \"REQUIRED\" means that the item is an absolute requirement of this specification.",
            "Adjusted": "These words are: \"MUST\" This word or the adjective \"REQUIRED\" means that the item is an absolute requirement of this specification."
        },
        {
            "Original": "o \"MUST NOT\" This phrase means that the item is an absolute prohibition of this specification.",
            "Adjusted": "\"MUST NOT\" This phrase means that the item is an absolute prohibition of this specification."
        },
        {
            "Original": "o \"SHOULD\" This word or the adjective \"RECOMMENDED\" means that there may exist valid reasons in particular circumstances to ignore this item, but the full implications should be understood and the case carefully weighed before choosing a different course.",
            "Adjusted": "\"SHOULD\" This word or the adjective \"RECOMMENDED\" means that there may exist valid reasons in particular circumstances to ignore this item, but the full implications should be understood and the case carefully weighed before choosing a different course."
        },
        {
            "Original": "o \"SHOULD NOT\" This phrase means that there may exist valid reasons in particular circumstances when the listed behavior is acceptable or even useful, but the full implications should be understood and the case carefully weighed before implementing any behavior described with this label.",
            "Adjusted": "\"SHOULD NOT\" This phrase means that there may exist valid reasons in particular circumstances when the listed behavior is acceptable or even useful, but the full implications should be understood and the case carefully weighed before implementing any behavior described with this label."
        },
        {
            "Original": "o \"MAY\" This word or the adjective \"OPTIONAL\" means that this item is truly optional.",
            "Adjusted": "\"MAY\" This word or the adjective \"OPTIONAL\" means that this item is truly optional."
        },
        {
            "Original": "One vendor may choose to include the item because a particular marketplace requires it or because it enhances the product, for example; another vendor may omit the same item.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

3. The Client-Server Protocol:
{
    "The Client-Server Protocol": [
        {
            "Original": "DHCP uses the BOOTP message format defined inRFC 951 and given in table 1 and figure 1.",
            "Adjusted": "DHCP uses the BOOTP message format defined in RFC 951 and given in table 1 and figure 1."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The 'op' field of each DHCP message sent from a client to a server contains BOOTREQUEST.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "BOOTREPLY is used in the 'op' field of each DHCP message sent from a server to a client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The first four octets of the 'options' field of the DHCP message contain the (decimal) values 99, 130, 83 and 99, respectively (this is the same magic cookie as is defined in RFC 1497 [17]).",
            "Adjusted": "The first four octets of the 'options' field of the DHCP message contain the (decimal) values 99, 130, 83 and 99, respectively, which is the same magic cookie as defined in RFC 1497 [17]."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The remainder of the 'options' field consists of a list of tagged parameters that are called \"options\".",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "All of the \"vendor extensions\" listed in RFC 1497 are also DHCP options.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "RFC 1533 gives the complete set of options defined for use with DHCP.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Several options have been defined so far.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "One particular option - the \"DHCP message type\" option - must be included in every DHCP message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This option defines the \"type\" of the DHCP message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Additional options may be allowed, required, or not allowed, depending on the DHCP message type.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Throughout this document, DHCP messages that include a 'DHCP message type' option will be referred to by the type of the message; e.g., a DHCP message with 'DHCP message type' option type 1 will be referred to as a \"DHCPDISCOVER\" message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

3. The Client-Server Protocol -> 3.7 Whe:
{
    "3. The Client-Server Protocol -> 3.7 When clients should use DHCP": [
        {
            "Original": "A client SHOULD use DHCP to reacquire or verify its IP address and network parameters whenever the local network parameters may have changed; e.g., at system boot time or after a disconnection from the local network, as the local network configuration may change without the client's or user's knowledge.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If a client has knowledge of a previous network address and is unable to contact a local DHCP server, the client may continue to use the previous network address until the lease for that address expires.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the lease expires before the client can contact a DHCP server, the client must immediately discontinue use of the previous network address and may inform local users of the problem.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

2. Protocol Summary -> 2.2 Dynamic alloc:
{
    "2. Protocol Summary -> 2.2 Dynamic allocation of network addresses": [
        {
            "Original": "The second service provided by DHCP is the allocation of temporary or permanent network (IP) addresses to clients.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The basic mechanism for the dynamic allocation of network addresses is simple: a client requests the use of an address for some period of time.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The allocation mechanism (the collection of DHCP servers) guarantees not to reallocate that address within the requested time and attempts to return the same network address each time the client requests an address.",
            "Adjusted": "The allocation mechanism (the collection of DHCP servers) guarantees not to reallocate the requested address within the requested time and attempts to return the same network address each time the client requests an address."
        },
        {
            "Original": "In this document, the period over which a network address is allocated to a client is referred to as a \"lease\" [11].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client may extend its lease with subsequent requests.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client may issue a message to release the address back to the server when the client no longer needs the address.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client may ask for a permanent assignment by asking for an infinite lease.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Even when assigning \"permanent\" addresses, a server may choose to give out lengthy but non-infinite leases to allow detection of the fact that the client has been retired.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In some environments it will be necessary to reassign network addresses due to exhaustion of available addresses.",
            "Adjusted": "In some environments reassignment of network addresses will be necessary due to exhaustion of available addresses."
        },
        {
            "Original": "In such environments, the allocation mechanism will reuse addresses whose lease has expired.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server should use whatever information is available in the configuration information repository to choose an address to reuse.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For example, the server may choose the least recently assigned address.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "As a consistency check, the allocating server SHOULD probe the reused address before allocating the address, e.g., with an ICMP echo request, and the client SHOULD probe the newly received address, e.g., with ARP.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

4. Specification of the DHCP client-serv:
{
    "4.3 DHCP server behavior": [
        {
            "Original": "A DHCP server processes incoming DHCP messages from a client based on the current state of the binding for that client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A DHCP server can receive the following messages from a client: o DHCPDISCOVER o DHCPREQUEST o DHCPDECLINE o DHCPRELEASE o DHCPINFORM Table 3 gives the use of the fields and options in a DHCP message by a server.",
            "Adjusted": "A DHCP server can receive the following messages from a client: DHCPDISCOVER, DHCPREQUEST, DHCPDECLINE, DHCPRELEASE, and DHCPINFORM. Table 3 describes the use of the fields and options in a DHCP message by a server."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The remainder of this section describes the action of the DHCP server for each possible incoming message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "4. Specification of the DHCP client-server protocol -> 4.3 DHCP server behavior -> 4.3.3 DHCPDECLINE message": [
        {
            "Original": "If the server receives a DHCPDECLINE message, the client has discovered through some other means that the suggested network address is already in use.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MUST mark the network address as not available and SHOULD notify the local system administrator of a possible configuration problem.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "4.3.4 DHCPRELEASE message": [
        {
            "Original": "Upon receipt of a DHCPRELEASE message, the server marks the network address as not allocated.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server SHOULD retain a record of the client's initialization parameters for possible reuse in response to subsequent requests from the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

1. Introduction -> 1.2 Related Work:
{
    "1.2 Related Work": [
        {
            "Original": "There are several Internet protocols and related mechanisms that address some parts of the dynamic host configuration problem.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Reverse Address Resolution Protocol (RARP) [10] (through the extensions defined in the Dynamic RARP (DRARP) [5\"\")) explicitly addresses the problem of network address discovery, and includes an automatic IP address assignment mechanism.",
            "Adjusted": "The Reverse Address Resolution Protocol (RARP) [10] (through the extensions defined in the Dynamic RARP (DRARP) [5]) explicitly addresses the problem of network address discovery, and includes an automatic IP address assignment mechanism."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP) [20\"\")] provides for transport of a boot image from a boot server.",
            "Adjusted": "The Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP) [20] provides for transport of a boot image from a boot server."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) [16] provides for informing hosts of additional routers via \"ICMP redirect\" messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "ICMP also can provide subnet mask information through the \"ICMP mask request\" message and other information through the (obsolete) \"ICMP information request\" message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Hosts can locate routers through the ICMP router discovery mechanism [8].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "BOOTP is a transport mechanism for a collection of configuration information.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "BOOTP is also extensible, and official extensions [17] have been defined for several configuration parameters.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Morgan has proposed extensions to BOOTP for dynamic IP address assignment [15].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Network Information Protocol (NIP), used by the Athena project at MIT, is a distributed mechanism for dynamic IP address assignment [19\")].",
            "Adjusted": "The Network Information Protocol (NIP), used by the Athena project at MIT, is a distributed mechanism for dynamic IP address assignment [19]."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Resource Location Protocol RLP [1] provides for location of higher level services.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Sun Microsystems diskless workstations use a boot procedure that employs RARP, TFTP and an RPC mechanism called \"bootparams\" to deliver configuration information and operating system code to diskless hosts.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "(Sun Microsystems, Sun Workstation and SunOS are trademarks of Sun Microsystems, Inc.) Some Sun networks also use DRARP and an auto-installation mechanism to automate the configuration of new hosts in an existing network.",
            "Adjusted": "Some Sun networks also use DRARP and an auto-installation mechanism to automate the configuration of new hosts in an existing network."
        },
        {
            "Original": "In other related work, the path minimum transmission unit (MTU) discovery algorithm can determine the MTU of an arbitrary internet path [14].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) has been proposed as a transport protocol for resource location and selection [6].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Finally, the Host Requirements RFCs [3, 4] mention specific requirements for host reconfiguration and suggest a scenario for initial configuration of diskless hosts.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

3. The Client-Server Protocol -> 3.5 Cli:
{
    "3.5 Client parameters in DHCP": [
        {
            "Original": "Not all clients require initialization of all parameters listed inAppendix A.",
            "Adjusted": "Not all clients require initialization of all parameters listed in Appendix A."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Two techniques are used to reduce the number of parameters transmitted from the server to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "First, most of the parameters have defaults defined in the Host Requirements RFCs; if the client receives no parameters from the server that override the defaults, a client uses those default values.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Second, in its initial DHCPDISCOVER or DHCPREQUEST message, a client may provide the server with a list of specific parameters the client is interested in.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client includes a list of parameters in a DHCPDISCOVER message, it MUST include that list in any subsequent DHCPREQUEST messages.",
            "Adjusted": "If the client includes a list of parameters in a DHCPDISCOVER message, the client MUST include that list in any subsequent DHCPREQUEST messages."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client SHOULD include the 'maximum DHCP message size' option to let the server know how large the server may make its DHCP messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The parameters returned to a client may still exceed the space allocated to options in a DHCP message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In this case, two additional options flags (which must appear in the 'options' field of the message) indicate that the 'file' and 'sname' fields are to be used for options.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client can inform the server which configuration parameters the client is interested in by including the 'parameter request list' option.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The data portion of this option explicitly lists the options requested by tag number.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In addition, the client may suggest values for the network address and lease time in the DHCPDISCOVER message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client may include the 'requested IP address' option to suggest that a particular IP address be assigned, and may include the 'IP address lease time' option to suggest the lease time it would like.",
            "Adjusted": "The client may include the 'requested IP address' option to suggest that a particular IP address be assigned, and may include the 'IP address lease time' option to suggest the lease time the client would like."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Other options representing \"hints\" at configuration parameters are allowed in a DHCPDISCOVER or DHCPREQUEST message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "However, additional options may be ignored by servers, and multiple servers may, therefore, not return identical values for some options.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The 'requested IP address' option is to be filled in only in a DHCPREQUEST message when the client is verifying network parameters obtained previously.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client fills in the 'ciaddr' field only when correctly configured with an IP address in BOUND, RENEWING or REBINDING state.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If a server receives a DHCPREQUEST message with an invalid 'requested IP address', the server SHOULD respond to the client with a DHCPNAK message and may choose to report the problem to the system administrator.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server may include an error message in the 'message' option.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

4. Specification of the DHCP client-serv:
{
    "4. Specification of the DHCP client-server protocol -> 4.3 DHCP server behavior -> 4.3.5 DHCPINFORM message": [
        {
            "Original": "The server responds to a DHCPINFORM message by sending a DHCPACK message directly to the address given in the 'ciaddr' field of the DHCPINFORM message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MUST NOT send a lease expiration time to the client and SHOULD NOT fill in 'yiaddr'.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server includes other parameters in the DHCPACK message as defined insection 4.3.1.",
            "Adjusted": "The server includes other parameters in the DHCPACK message as defined in section 4.3.1."
        }
    ]
}

1. Introduction -> 1.6 Design goals:
{
    "1.6 Design goals": [
        {
            "Original": "The following list gives general design goals for DHCP.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "o DHCP should be a mechanism rather than a policy.",
            "Adjusted": "DHCP should be a mechanism rather than a policy."
        },
        {
            "Original": "DHCP must allow local system administrators control over configuration parameters where desired; e.g., local system administrators should be able to enforce local policies concerning allocation and access to local resources where desired.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "o Clients should require no manual configuration.",
            "Adjusted": "Clients should require no manual configuration."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Each client should be able to discover appropriate local configuration parameters without user intervention and incorporate those parameters into its own configuration.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "o Networks should require no manual configuration for individual clients.",
            "Adjusted": "Networks should require no manual configuration for individual clients."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Under normal circumstances, the network manager should not have to enter any per-client configuration parameters.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "o DHCP should not require a server on each subnet.",
            "Adjusted": "DHCP should not require a server on each subnet."
        },
        {
            "Original": "To allow for scale and economy, DHCP must work across routers or through the intervention of BOOTP relay agents.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "o A DHCP client must be prepared to receive multiple responses to a request for configuration parameters.",
            "Adjusted": "A DHCP client must be prepared to receive multiple responses to a request for configuration parameters."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Some installations may include multiple, overlapping DHCP servers to enhance reliability and increase performance.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "o DHCP must coexist with statically configured, non-participating hosts and with existing network protocol implementations.",
            "Adjusted": "DHCP must coexist with statically configured, non-participating hosts and with existing network protocol implementations."
        },
        {
            "Original": "o DHCP must interoperate with the BOOTP relay agent behavior as described by RFC 951 and by RFC 1542 [21].",
            "Adjusted": "DHCP must interoperate with the BOOTP relay agent behavior as described by RFC 951 and by RFC 1542 [21]."
        },
        {
            "Original": "o DHCP must provide service to existing BOOTP clients.",
            "Adjusted": "DHCP must provide service to existing BOOTP clients."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The following list gives design goals specific to the transmission of the network layer parameters.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "DHCP must: o Guarantee that any specific network address will not be in use by more than one DHCP client at a time, o Retain DHCP client configuration across DHCP client reboot.",
            "Adjusted": "DHCP must guarantee that any specific network address will not be in use by more than one DHCP client at a time, and retain DHCP client configuration across DHCP client reboot."
        },
        {
            "Original": "A DHCP client should, whenever possible, be assigned the same configuration parameters (e.g., network address) in response to each request, o Retain DHCP client configuration across server reboots, and, whenever possible, a DHCP client should be assigned the same configuration parameters despite restarts of the DHCP mechanism, o Allow automated assignment of configuration parameters to new clients to avoid hand configuration for new clients, o Support fixed or permanent allocation of configuration parameters to specific clients.",
            "Adjusted": "A DHCP client should, whenever possible, be assigned the same configuration parameters (e.g., network address) in response to each request. DHCP must retain DHCP client configuration across server reboots, and whenever possible, a DHCP client should be assigned the same configuration parameters despite restarts of the DHCP mechanism. DHCP must allow automated assignment of configuration parameters to new clients to avoid hand configuration for new clients, and support fixed or permanent allocation of configuration parameters to specific clients."
        }
    ]
}

4. Specification of the DHCP client-serv:
{
    "4.3.6 Client messages": [
        {
            "Original": "Table 4 details the differences between messages from clients in various states.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\--------------------------------------------------------------------- | |INIT-REBOOT |SELECTING |RENEWING |REBINDING | \\--------------------------------------------------------------------- |broad/unicast |broadcast |broadcast |unicast |broadcast | |server-ip |MUST NOT |MUST |MUST NOT |MUST NOT | |requested-ip |MUST |MUST |MUST NOT |MUST NOT | |ciaddr |zero |zero |IP address |IP address| \\--------------------------------------------------------------------- Table 4: Client messages from different states",
            "Adjusted": "Table 4 shows the differences between messages from clients in various states: INIT-REBOOT uses broadcast and MUST include requested-ip but MUST NOT include server-ip, with ciaddr zero; SELECTING uses broadcast and MUST include both server-ip and requested-ip, with ciaddr zero; RENEWING uses unicast and MUST NOT include server-ip or requested-ip, with ciaddr as the IP address; REBINDING uses broadcast and MUST NOT include server-ip or requested-ip, with ciaddr as the IP address."
        }
    ]
}

1. Introduction:
{
    "1. Introduction": [
        {
            "Original": "The Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) provides configuration parameters to Internet hosts.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "DHCP consists of two components: a protocol for delivering host-specific configuration parameters from a DHCP server to a host and a mechanism for allocation of network addresses to hosts.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "DHCP is built on a client-server model, where designated DHCP server hosts allocate network addresses and deliver configuration parameters to dynamically configured hosts.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Throughout the remainder of this document, the term \"server\" refers to a host providing initialization parameters through DHCP, and the term \"client\" refers to a host requesting initialization parameters from a DHCP server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A host should not act as a DHCP server unless explicitly configured to do so by a system administrator.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The diversity of hardware and protocol implementations in the Internet would preclude reliable operation if random hosts were allowed to respond to DHCP requests.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For example, IP requires the setting of many parameters within the protocol implementation software.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Because IP can be used on many dissimilar kinds of network hardware, values for those parameters cannot be guessed or assumed to have correct defaults.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Also, distributed address allocation schemes depend on a polling/defense mechanism for discovery of addresses that are already in use.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "IP hosts may not always be able to defend their network addresses, so that such a distributed address allocation scheme cannot be guaranteed to avoid allocation of duplicate network addresses.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "DHCP supports three mechanisms for IP address allocation.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In \"automatic allocation\", DHCP assigns a permanent IP address to a client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In \"dynamic allocation\", DHCP assigns an IP address to a client for a limited period of time (or until the client explicitly relinquishes the address).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In \"manual allocation\", a client's IP address is assigned by the network administrator, and DHCP is used simply to convey the assigned address to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A particular network will use one or more of these mechanisms, depending on the policies of the network administrator.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Dynamic allocation is the only one of the three mechanisms that allows automatic reuse of an address that is no longer needed by the client to which it was assigned.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Thus, dynamic allocation is particularly useful for assigning an address to a client that will be connected to the network only temporarily or for sharing a limited pool of IP addresses among a group of clients that do not need permanent IP addresses.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Dynamic allocation may also be a good choice for assigning an IP address to a new client being permanently connected to a network where IP addresses are sufficiently scarce that it is important to reclaim them when old clients are retired.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Manual allocation allows DHCP to be used to eliminate the error-prone process of manually configuring hosts with IP addresses in environments where (for whatever reasons) it is desirable to manage IP address assignment outside of the DHCP mechanisms.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The format of DHCP messages is based on the format of BOOTP messages, to capture the BOOTP relay agent behavior described as part of the BOOTP specification [7\"\"), 21] and to allow interoperability of existing BOOTP clients with DHCP servers.",
            "Adjusted": "The format of DHCP messages is based on the format of BOOTP messages, to capture the BOOTP relay agent behavior described as part of the BOOTP specification and to allow interoperability of existing BOOTP clients with DHCP servers."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Using BOOTP relay agents eliminates the necessity of having a DHCP server on each physical network segment.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

4. Specification of the DHCP client-serv:
{
    "4. Specification of the DHCP client-server protocol -> 4.4 DHCP client behavior -> 4.4.6 DHCPRELEASE": [
        {
            "Original": "If the client no longer requires use of its assigned network address (e.g., the client is gracefully shut down), the client sends a DHCPRELEASE message to the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that the correct operation of DHCP does not depend on the transmission of DHCPRELEASE messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "4.2 DHCP server administrative controls": [
        {
            "Original": "DHCP servers are not required to respond to every DHCPDISCOVER and DHCPREQUEST message they receive.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For example, a network administrator, to retain stringent control over the clients attached to the network, may choose to configure DHCP servers to respond only to clients that have been previously registered through some external mechanism.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The DHCP specification describes only the interactions between clients and servers when the clients and servers choose to interact; it is beyond the scope of the DHCP specification to describe all of the administrative controls that system administrators might want to use.",
            "Adjusted": "The DHCP specification describes only the interactions between clients and servers when the clients and servers choose to interact; describing all of the administrative controls that system administrators might want to use is beyond the scope of the DHCP specification."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Specific DHCP server implementations may incorporate any controls or policies desired by a network administrator.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In some environments, a DHCP server will have to consider the values of the vendor class options included in DHCPDISCOVER or DHCPREQUEST messages when determining the correct parameters for a particular client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A DHCP server needs to use some unique identifier to associate a client with its lease.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client MAY choose to explicitly provide the identifier through the 'client identifier' option.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client supplies a 'client identifier', the client MUST use the same 'client identifier' in all subsequent messages, and the server MUST use that identifier to identify the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client does not provide a 'client identifier' option, the server MUST use the contents of the 'chaddr' field to identify the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "It is crucial for a DHCP client to use an identifier unique within the subnet to which the client is attached in the 'client identifier' option.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Use of 'chaddr' as the client's unique identifier may cause unexpected results, as that identifier may be associated with a hardware interface that could be moved to a new client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Some sites may choose to use a manufacturer's serial number as the 'client identifier', to avoid unexpected changes in a clients network address due to transfer of hardware interfaces among computers.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Sites may also choose to use a DNS name as the 'client identifier', causing address leases to be associated with the DNS name rather than a specific hardware box.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "DHCP clients are free to use any strategy in selecting a DHCP server among those from which the client receives a DHCPOFFER message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client implementation of DHCP SHOULD provide a mechanism for the user to select directly the 'vendor class identifier' values.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "4.4.2 Initialization with known network address": [
        {
            "Original": "The client begins in INIT-REBOOT state and sends a DHCPREQUEST message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client MUST insert its known network address as a 'requested IP address' option in the DHCPREQUEST message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client may request specific configuration parameters by including the 'parameter request list' option.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client generates and records a random transaction identifier and inserts that identifier into the 'xid' field.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client records its own local time for later use in computing the lease expiration.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client MUST NOT include a 'server identifier' in the DHCPREQUEST message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client then broadcasts the DHCPREQUEST on the local hardware broadcast address to the 'DHCP server' UDP port.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Once a DHCPACK message with an 'xid' field matching that in the client's DHCPREQUEST message arrives from any server, the client is initialized and moves to BOUND state.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client records the lease expiration time as the sum of the time at which the DHCPREQUEST message was sent and the duration of the lease from the DHCPACK message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "4.4.4 Use of broadcast and unicast": [
        {
            "Original": "The DHCP client broadcasts DHCPDISCOVER, DHCPREQUEST and DHCPINFORM messages, unless the client knows the address of a DHCP server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client unicasts DHCPRELEASE messages to the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Because the client is declining the use of the IP address supplied by the server, the client broadcasts DHCPDECLINE messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "When the DHCP client knows the address of a DHCP server, in either INIT or REBOOTING state, the client may use that address in the DHCPDISCOVER or DHCPREQUEST rather than the IP broadcast address.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client may also use unicast to send DHCPINFORM messages to a known DHCP server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client receives no response to DHCP messages sent to the IP address of a known DHCP server, the DHCP client reverts to using the IP broadcast address.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

